    "summary": "Objection to \"constitutive nature\" — nature collides with 性",
    "content": "My strongest objection is the **\"nature\" collision.**\n\nThe 集体利益 essay uses 人性 (human nature) on line 21. If 德 is rendered \"constitutive nature,\" then the reader encounters \"nature\" in two unrelated technical roles: 德 = \"constitutive nature\" (the defining quality of any kind of thing) and 性 = \"nature\" (as in human nature). In the 道德仁义礼 passage, the author discusses 人德 (the 德 of humans, i.e., 仁). If 德 = \"constitutive nature,\" then 人德 becomes \"the constitutive nature of humans\" -- which sounds identical to \"human nature\" (人性). But these are different concepts in the author's framework.\n\n\"Inherent character\" avoids this collision. \"The inherent character of humans\" is clearly distinct from \"human nature.\"\n\nI acknowledge \"constitutive\" is a better adjective than \"inherent\" on its own merits -- it is more neutral on the innate/constructed question. But the noun it modifies creates the problem. If the proposal were \"constitutive character,\" I would consider switching. But \"constitutive nature\" specifically is blocked by the 性 collision."
